More stric list item handling.This make list item handling more strict, hopefully preventingnunexpected behavior becuase of uninitialized memory, and making itneasier to debug such issues.nnList item usage rules:nn- A list item must be initialized using new nn_list_item_init(),n  replacing nn_list_item_nil().n- If you ignore the rule above, inserting an uninitialized list itemn  assert :-)n- A list item should be terminated using new nn_list_item_term(). Thisn  function assert that the item is nill and is not part of any list.nnImplementation changes:nnTo support static initalization, NN_LIST_INITIALIZER macro was added.nnThe special nil list item value was changed to -1 (0xffffffffffffffff).nThis make it easier to expose the value for other modules in a safe way,nand to detect nil items while debugging. This also ensure that codentrying to use nil list item will segfault.nnAll code was modified to initialize and terminate list items properly.nNote that the best place to terminate list item is not always clear, asnsome objects not have a termination function (e.g. xxx_term). This partnof the patch needs good review.nnThe patch reveal possible data race in the tcp_shutdown test - the testnfails now when trying to insert an invalid list item:nnnext = 0xffffffffffffffff,nprev = 0x23ffffffffffffnnSigned-off-by: Martin Sustrik <sustrik@250bpm.com>n

nn_list_item_nil function removedSigned-off-by: Martin Sustrik <sustrik@250bpm.com>n

nn_queue_item_init & nn_queue_item_term addedThis patch ensures that no uninitilised data are involvednwhen working with queues.nnSigned-off-by: Martin Sustrik <sustrik@250bpm.com>n

nn_symbol queries the names and values of nanomsg symbols./*  Returns the symbol name (e.g. NN_REQ) and value at a specified index.   */n/*  If the index is out-of-range, returns NULL and sets errno to EINVAL   */n/*  General usage is to start at i=0 and iterate until NULL is returned.  */nNN_EXPORT const char *nn_symbol (int i, int* value);nnWith the addition of nn_symbol to dynamically query nanomsg symbols (constants),nthe nn_version function is obsolete.  C programs can get the version informationndirectly from the #defines and other languages can extract it from the variousnNN_VERSION_* symbols.nnSigned-off-by: Martin Sustrik <sustrik@250bpm.com>n

fixes #978 nanomsg IPC on Windows is very fragileThis is critical for hardening use cases with other IPC clientsnsuch as nng or mangos.  The old code made some very incorrectnassumptions about the atomicity of named pipes and ReadFile.nnWe've changed the code so that if ReadFile (or WSARecv incidentally)never returns a partial read, we keep going.nnThis solves a critial assertion error, and greatly improvesnthe crash resistance of nanomsg when using IPC on Windows.n
